{"award_age":45.0,"bio_image":"full\/56f9eb8fdedbf43fdc20bc6fb510d6002f392a55.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United Kingdom","date_of_birth":"1857-05-13T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1932-09-16T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/7\/76\/Ronald_Ross.jpg\/220px-Ronald_Ross.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ronald_Ross","mini_bio":"<p><b>Sir Ronald Ross<\/b>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Knight_Commander_of_the_Order_of_the_Bath\" title=\"Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath\" class=\"mw-redirect\">KCB<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Royal_Society\" title=\"Royal Society\">FRS<\/a><sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ronald_Ross#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-rajkumar_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ronald_Ross#cite_note-rajkumar-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> (13 May 1857 \u2013 16 September 1932), was an Indian-born British <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Medical_doctor\" title=\"Medical doctor\" class=\"mw-redirect\">medical doctor<\/a> who received the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_for_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine<\/a> in 1902 for his work on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Malaria\" title=\"Malaria\">malaria<\/a>, becoming the first <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_Kingdom\" title=\"United Kingdom\">British<\/a> Nobel laureate, and the first born outside of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Europe\" title=\"Europe\">Europe<\/a>. His <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/History_of_malaria\" title=\"History of malaria\">discovery of the malarial parasite<\/a> in the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Gastrointestinal_tract\" title=\"Gastrointestinal tract\" class=\"mw-redirect\">gastrointestinal tract<\/a> of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mosquito\" title=\"Mosquito\">mosquito<\/a> led to the realisation that <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Malaria\" title=\"Malaria\">malaria<\/a> was transmitted by mosquitoes, and laid the foundation for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Vector_control\" title=\"Vector control\">combating the disease<\/a>. He was quite a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Polymath\" title=\"Polymath\">polymath<\/a>, writing a number of poems, published several novels, and composed songs. He was also an amateur artist and natural mathematician. He worked in the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Indian_Medical_Service\" title=\"Indian Medical Service\">Indian Medical Service<\/a> for 25 years. It was during his service that he made the groundbreaking medical discovery. After resigning from his service in India, he joined the faculty of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Liverpool_School_of_Tropical_Medicine\" title=\"Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine\">Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine<\/a>, and continued as Professor and Chair of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Tropical_Medicine\" title=\"Tropical Medicine\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Tropical Medicine<\/a> of the institute for 10 years. In 1926 he became Director-in-Chief of the Ross Institute and Hospital for Tropical Diseases, which was established in honour of his works. He remained there until his death.<sup id=\"cite_ref-cdc_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ronald_Ross#cite_note-cdc-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-kakk_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ronald_Ross#cite_note-kakk-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Ronald Ross","place_of_birth":"Almora ,  India","place_of_death":"London, England, United Kingdom","text":"Ronald Ross , Physiology or Medicine, 1902","year":1902.0}